      <div xml:id="NA251-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu ciṟaippuṟamākac ceṟippaṟivuṟīiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what informs of confinement when [HE] is behind the fence.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA251">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            neṭunī raruviya kaṭumpāṭ ṭāṅkaṭ</l>
<l>            piṇimuta laraiya peruṅkal vāḻaik</l>
<l>            koḻumuta lāykaṉi manti kavaru</l>
<l>            naṉmalai nāṭaṉai nayavā yāmava</l>
<l>            ṉaṉipē raṉpi ṉiṉkura lōppi </l>
<l>            niṟpuṟaṅ kāttaluṅ kāṇpōy nīyeṉ</l>
<l>            ṟaḷirēr mēṉit tolkavi ṉaḻiyap</l>
<l>            palipeṟu kaṭavuṭ pēṇik kaliciṟantu</l>
<l>            tuṭaṅkunilap pāvai yuṭaṅkupīḷ kavarun</l>
<l>            tōṭiṭaṅ kōṭāy kiḷarntu </l>
<l>            nīṭiṉai viḷaimō vāḻiya tiṉaiyē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>You, you see [me]<note place="foot">Actually, it is tempting here to read a vocative phrase: "o you who see", but <term xml:lang="ta">kāṇpōy</term> ought to be a finite verb. In any case the post-positioned subject <term xml:lang="ta">nī</term> is meant to have vocative force here.</note> protecting you too,</l>
<l>we, longing for the man from the land of good mountains,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the she-monkey seizes the choice ripe fruit with rich base<note place="foot">T.V.G. interprets here <term xml:lang="ta">koḻu mutal</term> as the especially good first yield of the plant.</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">of the plantain on the big stones, [its] trunk at the base fettered to</l>
<l rend="indent3">that place of rushing songs from the waterfall of the long water,</l>
<l>scaring [the birds] away from your ears, in very great love for him.</l>
<l>Coming up don’t bend in<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tōṭu iṭam</term>: <term xml:lang="ta">iṭam</term> poses a probalem here. We can either take is as a mere locative suffix (see above) or consider the possibility of its use as a verbal prefix, <term xml:lang="ta">iṭam-kōṭu</term>, which is, however, not backed up by the TL.</note> the leaves, [at a time] when,</l>
<l rend="indent">they will seize [your] ears immediately for the image on the raw ground,</l>
<l rend="indent2">while the bustling is great in honouring the god who obtains offerings,</l>
<l rend="indent3">so that the old beauty of my sprout-like body will perish,</l>
<l>– take a long time to ripen, may you live, millet.</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="5b">
    <l>scaring away [from you the birds] with sweet voice...</l>
</lg>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="5c">
    <l>scaring away [from you those with] sweet voice (i.e. the birds)</l>
</lg>
      </lg>
